r ecosystem:

I think Apple dramatically overestimated developers=E2=80=99 willingness to=
 come on board, and I=E2=80=99ve spoken to a lot of developers, I know this=
 to be true. There=E2=80=99s a lot of people that are sitting on the sideli=
nes, waiting to spend their venture capital money on building for the Visio=
n Pro until there=E2=80=99s critical mass of users. They could put an app i=
n the Vision Pro store and price it even highly because they know people ar=
e willing to pay more money, but there=E2=80=99s just not enough people the=
re.

I don=E2=80=99t know if it=E2=80=99s true that Apple didn=E2=80=99t seed mo=
ney into the developer ecosystem, but I don=E2=80=99t think they did, and I=
 think this was a really serious mistake that could have been easily avoide=
d. I mean it=E2=80=99s the opposite to what Meta has done over the years by=
 really funding studios=E2=80=A6

I think Apple just assumed that they would be there, but they=E2=80=99re no=
t there. So that is probably a big correction that they=E2=80=99re making a=
t the moment. It=E2=80=99s just trying to re-energize the ecosystem. I know=
 that Tim Cook is personally meeting with VR developers in China in a recen=
t trip because a lot of these people reached out to share their excitement =
with meeting the big man, so kudos to him, I think that=E2=80=99s great, I =
think that=E2=80=99s what they have to do because it=E2=80=99s a mistake th=
at has to be corrected.

This seems right to me: it seems like Apple, broadly speaking, just sort of=
 expected an ecosystem to materialize for the Vision Pro like one did for t=
he iPhone; the difference is this isn=E2=80=99t a better phone =E2=80=94 wh=
ich people were already buying =E2=80=94 but an entirely new category that =
needs to be given a reason to exist. The best hope at this point, two month=
s in with basically zero new content or meaningful new experiences, is that=
 Apple will get started on a project it should have started a long time ago=
.

The first step? Designate a =E2=80=9CDirectly Responsible Individual=E2=80=
=9D. Adam Lashinsky explained the concept in Fortune in 2011 ( https://fort=
une.com/2011/08/25/how-apple-works-inside-the-worlds-biggest-startup/ ) :

At Apple there is never any confusion as to who is responsible for what. In=
ternal Applespeak even has a name for it, the =E2=80=9CDRI,=E2=80=9D or dir=
ectly responsible individual. Often the DRI=E2=80=99s name will appear on a=
n agenda for a meeting, so everybody knows who is responsible. =E2=80=9CAny=
 effective meeting at Apple will have an action list,=E2=80=9D says a forme=
r employee. =E2=80=9CNext to each action item will be the DRI.=E2=80=9D A c=
ommon phrase heard around Apple when someone is trying to learn the right c=
ontact on a project: =E2=80=9CWho=E2=80=99s the DRI on that?=E2=80=9D

Who is the DRI for Apple Vision Pro? The WWDC (pre-recorded) introduction o=
f the Apple Vision Pro featured, in order:

* CEO Tim Cook introduced the device
* Alan Dye, Vice President of Human Interface Design, introduced the user i=
nterface
* Allessandra McGinnis, Apple Vision Pro Product Manager, talked through a =
(pre-recorded) demo
* En Kelly, Senior Engineering Program Manager of the Technology Developmen=
t Group, talked through a (pre-recorded) demo
* Cook brought on Disney CEO Bob Iger to talk about Disney=E2=80=99s invest=
ment in building a Vision Pro experience
* Richard Howarth, Vice President of Industrial Design, introduced the hard=
ware design
* Mike Rockwell, Vice President of the Technology Development Group, introd=
uced the technology undergirding the Vision Pro
* Susan Prescott, Vice President of Worldwide Developer Relations, talked a=
bout the developer story
* Rockwell returned to talk about privacy and security, summarized the intr=
oduction, and announced the price and that the device would be available in=
 early 2024

No one in this video is obviously in charge of the project as a whole. Rock=
well seems the most invested in the device, but one certainly didn=E2=80=99=
t get the impression he has any role in the developer ecosystem or Apple TV=
+; I will note that, to Rockwell=E2=80=99s credit, the parts he does seem i=
nvolved in =E2=80=94 the actual hardware =E2=80=94 is the most impressive p=
art of the Vision Pro story. That story, though, needs to be about more tha=
n hardware: the Vision Pro needs an ecosystem, that includes not just hardw=
are and retail but also apps and immersive experiences. That doesn=E2=80=99=
t exist, and the fact I=E2=80=99m not sure who to blame may in fact be the =
root of the problem.

